results.notes:
Growing on a pile of wood pieces and tree leaves; Same place than observation 224024 and of my other observations in coprinoid mushrooms since then.

From Uljé key:

KEY TO THE SECTIONS AND SUBSECTIONS
1. Pileus with veil, without setules or setae.
4. Veil mainly consisting of elongate elements; section Coprinus
5. Veil abundant, loosely attached and easy removable from pileus; basidiocarps very small to small, a few medium-sized; stipe 1-4(-6) mm wide; pileus white to greyish below veil, rare brown; never annulus on stipe.
7. Veil made up of branched, diverculate, thin- or thickwalled hyphae; if elements in chains with distinct end cells then the walls are thickened and yellow-brown; subsect. Alachuani Sing.

COPRINUS SUBSECTION ALACHUANI
Basidiocarps very small to medium-sized; expanded pileus 6-60 mm. Pileus with veil made up of weakly to strongly diverticulate, and then often thick-walled elements. Stipe smooth, but in most cases covered with very small velar flocks, especially at base (subsect. Alachuani Sing.).
1. Spores warty.
28. Spores amygdaloid: C. echinosporus
28. Spores ellipsoid, ovoid.
29. Basidia 4-spored: C. phlyctidosporus
29. Basidia 2-spored: C. rugosobisporus

As mentioned in the key, if the spores are amygdaloid, then C. echinosporus. I think that we can rule out this species, since in spite of the existence of amygdaloid spores, the majority is ellipsoid to ovoid. So the question relies on the 2- or 4-spored basidia. I should mention that I could see some (small number) of the basidia but could not be certain, they seemed like 2-spored. On the other hand, the dimensions obtained for the spores fit better in C. phlyctidosporus than in C. rugosobisporus, the latter being wider. For the spores I got the following dimensions:
(8.2) 8.9 – 10.7 (11.4) x (5.7) 6.1 – 6.7 (7.1) µm

results.notes:
Behold, unexpectedly …
I am a declared lover of coprinoid mushrooms, but I have not found as many as would like. Well, this year only on this site found more different species than in all my past. There are such things!

Growing on a pile of wood pieces and tree leaves; Same place than observation 224024 and of my other observations in coprinoid mushrooms since then.
Cap with about 1.2 cm in diameter. Very similar to my previous observation 226310; I believe to be of the same species or a closed/related one.

Application of Uljé’s keys:

KEY TO THE SECTIONS AND SUBSECTIONS
1. Pileus without veil, smooth or with setulae and/or setae; section Pseudocoprinus
2. Stipe and pileus with setulae and/or setae; subsect. Setulosi J. Lange

KEY TO THE SPECIES IN SUBSECTION SETULOSI

1. Spores smooth
NOTE: As can be seen in the photos the spores are not entirelly smooth, but may not be considered as warty. Moreover, choosing the other option we will be send to a group of specimens with different morphology (larger), which was considered in others of my observations.

3. Spores mitriform or angular, not ellipsoid, ovoid or oblong
32. Spores hexagonal (more or less 6-angled) in front view: C. marculentus.
NOTE: The spores are markedly hexagonal in front view, but mixed with the others in other views could be difficult to decide.

Taking this exercise into account and also that the other features observed, namely the form of the pileocystidia, are in accordance with the description, I suppose that the species was reached.
In my first observation of this species, observation 226309, and in observation 226310, I had already reached a similar conclusion but I hesitated, mainly on the base of the spore dimensions, which were a bit too low in lenght. Now, I think that all these observations correspond to the same species: C. marculentus.

results.notes:
Code: Bot_829/2014_DSC3183
Picture file names: from Lepiota oreadiformis_raw_1 to Lepiota oreadiformis_raw_7.

Habitat: grassland, mountain pasture; near mixed wood edge; moderately inclined mountain slope; southeast aspect; shallow soil, skeletal, calcareous ground; open, sunny place; dry and relatively warm place; exposed to direct rain; average precipitations ~ 3.000 mm/year, average temperature 7-9 deg C, elevation 620 m (2.050 feet), alpine phytogeographical region.

Substratum: soil among grass.

Place: Lower Trenta valley, between villages Soča and Trenta, right bank of river Soča, ‘Na Melu’ pasture near Trenta 2b cottage, on the uppermost part of the pasture; East Julian Alps, Posočje, Slovenia EC.

Comments: Lepiota clypeolaria is a much more frequent species in my country. Contrary, Lepiota oreadiformis is rare. Statistically the first option seems therefore more probable. However, the sporocarps found were significantly smaller than of typical Lepiota clypeolaria, mature specimens lacked distinct annulus, and habitat of this find doesn’t seem compatible with Lepiota clypeolaria at all (it grows in woods). Therefore it seems that Lepiota oreadiformis is a better fit. Typical habitat of this species are open places on dry, extensively used, not fertilized, base rich grassland, which perfectly fits to this find. With respect to pilei surface quite large differences can be found on pictures in the literature. Frequently pictures show pilei with smoother surface. However, authors state: pilei covered by ‘distant, granular squamules, radially wrinkled’ (Ref.:1), ‘lightly covered by small, ocher brown, radially fibrous squamules’ (Ref.4) and ‘minutely felty when young, but breaking up into scales on ageing’ (Ref.:2). Also, most pictures show pilei with less prominent buckle. So, I am not completely sure the determination is correct. Growing scattered and in small groups; about ten pilei present; pilei diameter 3 – 4 (5) cm, stipe 4 – 6 cm long and 4 – 5 mm in diameter; on young pilei a faint, white, fibrous ‘ring’ noticeable, mature fruitbodies with no observable ring; SP faint, whitish-beige with slight green tint, oac6.

results.notes:
Growing on a pile of wood pieces and tree leaves; Same place than observation 224024 and of my other observations in coprinoid mushrooms since then.

Application of Uljé’s keys with some comments in square brackets:

1. Spores smooth [The spores are bigger than in the other species already analyzed; looking to FAN6 or to Uljé’s keys, there are only a few species with such big spores]
2. Basidia 4-spored [see the attached photos]
3. Spores ellipsoid, ovoid or oblong [see the attached photos]
4. Pileocystidia with distinctly tapering neck [see the atteched photos]
5. No velar spherocysts on pileipellis [no velar spherocysts were observed ]
6. Germ pore eccentric (sometimes only slightly) [clearly eccentric as can be seen in the attached photos]
7. With pleurocystidia [see the attached photos]
8. On dung
9. Clamps-connections absent: C. congregatus
9. Clamps-connections present: C. ephemerus
8. Not on dung
10. Av. Q of spores c. 1.25: C. eurysporus
10. Av. Q of spores c. 1.60: C. sp. Uljé 877

This is the doutbful point in the key. The features observed are that of C. ephemerus, which in the key is placed to live on dung. However, in the description of that species is written “Habitat: On cow-dung, but also on decaying straw”. Since cow-dung for sure doesn’t exist at this place (it could at most have some pieces of horse dung), I think that the pile where it was found could have some straw, in addition to the pieces of wood and leaves from trees. The similar C. congregatus has smaller spores (~ 2 µm less in lenght).
The species mentioned in the key not living in dung are very different. Thus I believe that this is Coprinellus ephemerus (the current name for that species).

results.notes:
Code: Bot_903/2015_DSC7972 (042257)

Habitat: mountain lake shore, in willow thickets, among tall herbs; flat terrain, calcareous alluvial, skeletal ground; in shade, humid place, partly protected from direct rain by tree canopies, average precipitations ~ 2.800 mm/year, average temperature 5-7 deg C, elevation 960 m (3.150 feet), alpine phytogeographical region.

Substratum: fallen, dead trunk of Salix eleagnos in its initial disintegration stage.

Place: Iof di Montasio region, south shore of Raibel Lake (Rabeljsko jezero), south of village Rabelj (Cave del Predil), Jezernica valley (Val Rio del Lago), borderline between East and West Julian Alps, Friuli-Venezia-Giulia, Italy EC.

Comments: Assuming this find belongs to Polyporus Fr. (sens.lat.) large measured spores point to the group Polyporus s.str. with only two members in Europe, namely Polyoprus tuberaster and Polyporus squamosus (Ref.1). Since Polyporus tuberster grows on ground from a sclerotium the only candidate from this group remains Polyporus squamoss. However, density of pores (measured 5-6 pores/mm; typical for Polyporus squamosus 1-2/mm) apparently exclude this option. Also, pilei surface do not show even a trace of radially arranged darker squamules so typical for Polyporus squamosus. So, this option seems out. On the other hand macroscopic traits fit well to Polyporud varius. Pilei size, density of pores, pilei color (for young pilei), decurrent pores, black, short, relatively thin stipe and substratum all speak in favor of this determination. However, measured spores are way too big.
I have no convincing explanation for this discrepancy. May be that the sporocarps found were too young to sporulate and that the spores measured belong to some other fungi in the vicinity of the find? SP was (if at all) very faint, practically invisible for the naked eye.

Growing solitary and in a single group of four pilei fuzzed at the base; pilei diameter up to 6.5 cm; stipe short, thin compared to pilei diameter, almost entirely black; context firm, leathery, almost difficult to cut; when dry very hard; context slowly darkening to light brown when cut; pore surface also darkening to light brown when handled; SP almost none.

Nikon D700/Nikkor Micro 105mm/f2.8 and Samsung Tablet SM-P605
